org.assertj.swing.core.matcher

Class FrameMatcher

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.assertj.swing.core.AbstractComponentMatcher
      • org.assertj.swing.core.GenericTypeMatcher<T>
        • org.assertj.swing.core.matcher.NamedComponentMatcherTemplate<java.awt.Frame>

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ComponentMatcher, ResettableComponentMatcher

    public final class FrameMatcher
extends NamedComponentMatcherTemplate<java.awt.Frame>
    Matches AWT or Swing Frames by name, title or visibility on the screen.
    Author:
    Alex Ruiz

    • Method Detail

      • withName

        public static FrameMatcher withName(@Nullable
                    java.lang.String name)

        Creates a new FrameMatcher that matches an AWT or Swing Frame by name.

        The following code listing shows how to match a Frame by name and title: 

         FrameMatcher m = withName("myApp").andTitle("My App");

        The following code listing shows how to match a Frame, that should be showing on the screen, by name and title: 

         FrameMatcher m = withName("myApp").andTitle("My App").andShowing();
        Parameters:
        name - the id to match.
        Returns:
        the created matcher.

      • withTitle

        public static FrameMatcher withTitle(@Nonnull
                     java.lang.String title)

        Creates a new FrameMatcher that matches an AWT or Swing Frame by title.

        The following code listing shows how to match a Frame by title: 

         FrameMatcher m = withTitle("My App");

        The following code listing shows how to match a Frame, that should be showing on the screen, by title: 

         FrameMatcher m = withTitle("My App").andShowing();
        Parameters:
        title - the title to match. It can be a regular expression.
        Returns:
        the created matcher.

      • withTitle

        @Nonnull
public static FrameMatcher withTitle(@Nonnull
                             java.util.regex.Pattern pattern)

        Creates a new FrameMatcher that matches an AWT or Swing Frame by title.

        The following code listing shows how to match a Frame by title, using a regular expression matcher: 

         FrameMatcher m = withTitle(Pattern.compile("My.*"));

        The following code listing shows how to match a Frame, that should be showing on the screen, by title: 

         FrameMatcher m = withTitle(Pattern.compile("My.*")).andShowing();
        Parameters:
        pattern - the title to match.
        Returns:
        the created matcher.

      • isMatching

        @RunsInCurrentThread
protected boolean isMatching(@Nonnull
                                     java.awt.Frame frame)

        Indicates whether the name and title of the given AWT or Swing Frame match the ones in this matcher.

        Note: This method is accessed in the current executing thread. Such thread may or may not be the event dispatch thread (EDT.) Client code must call this method from the EDT.

        Specified by:
        isMatching in class GenericTypeMatcher<java.awt.Frame>
        Parameters:
        frame - the Frame to match.
        Returns:
        true if the title in the Frame is equal to the title in this matcher, false otherwise.
